00:00:21.637 --> 00:00:24.220
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Let me quick
do a wrap-up of where we are,

00:00:24.220 --> 00:00:27.370
just so you remember
our context.

00:00:27.370 --> 00:00:29.080
Class one was really
all about growth.

00:00:29.080 --> 00:00:30.760
Economics, as you
all know, when we

00:00:30.760 --> 00:00:34.870
talked about the contributions
that Solow and Romer made,

00:00:34.870 --> 00:00:39.580
and they really forced us to
look at what we could call

00:00:39.580 --> 00:00:42.520
two direct innovation factors.

00:00:42.520 --> 00:00:44.350
What Solow called
technological-related

00:00:44.350 --> 00:00:46.420
innovation we can
sort of translate that

00:00:46.420 --> 00:00:51.820
as R&D. And Romer, the talent
base human capital engagement

00:00:51.820 --> 00:00:54.040
research was his key term.

00:00:54.040 --> 00:00:58.030
We read Dale Jorgensen,
and Jorgensen showed us

00:00:58.030 --> 00:01:00.160
that technology-based
innovation really

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:03.190
was the driving causative
factor in the great growth

00:01:03.190 --> 00:01:05.379
spurt of the 1990s.

00:01:05.379 --> 00:01:08.050
That was the innovation wave
around the IT revolution,

00:01:08.050 --> 00:01:09.460
as you remember.

00:01:09.460 --> 00:01:12.040
And we talked about how there
were direct innovation factors.

00:01:12.040 --> 00:01:15.970
So Romer contributed those,
arguably, and others.

00:01:15.970 --> 00:01:18.560
But there are also
many indirect factors.

00:01:18.560 --> 00:01:19.060
All right?

00:01:19.060 --> 00:01:20.755
So less critical
factors, but this

00:01:20.755 --> 00:01:24.310
is a complex ecosystem
of innovation.

00:01:24.310 --> 00:01:30.340
Richard Nelson gives us a third
innovation factor, looking

00:01:30.340 --> 00:01:34.870
at innovation as a system and
the organizational elements

00:01:34.870 --> 00:01:37.240
within it and the connectedness
of the different actors

00:01:37.240 --> 00:01:38.948
and the strength of
the different actors,

00:01:38.948 --> 00:01:43.330
so that gives us a systems'
way of evaluating an innovation

00:01:43.330 --> 00:01:49.000
system, whether it's national
or regional or local.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:54.130
Nelson gives us a perspective
on how to look at that system.

00:01:54.130 --> 00:02:00.580
Atkinson and others contributed
on innovation wave theory.

00:02:00.580 --> 00:02:02.560
The way in which
economies grow is

00:02:02.560 --> 00:02:07.180
that they bring these new
innovation waves on and scale

00:02:07.180 --> 00:02:08.919
them up over an
extended period of time.

00:02:08.919 --> 00:02:11.880
They start very gradually,
finally reach a point

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:13.120
where they can scale quickly.

00:02:13.120 --> 00:02:15.805
There's always a bust, then
they scale more gradually.

00:02:15.805 --> 00:02:17.680
That's kind of the stages
we've talked about.

00:02:17.680 --> 00:02:20.560
We're now with
the IT revolution.

00:02:20.560 --> 00:02:22.120
Charles Schulz
taught us to kind of

00:02:22.120 --> 00:02:28.390
be aware of industrial policy.

00:02:28.390 --> 00:02:31.270
And we talked a lot about
the government role here,

00:02:31.270 --> 00:02:35.170
but that's a cautionary tale
of some problematic aspects

00:02:35.170 --> 00:02:36.940
of a governmental role.

00:02:36.940 --> 00:02:39.730
Classes 3 and 4 were really
about advanced manufacturing,

00:02:39.730 --> 00:02:43.040
which we did as our
first big case study.

00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:45.610
Obviously we'll have another
big case study today.

00:02:45.610 --> 00:02:47.950
We had health last week.

00:02:47.950 --> 00:02:50.560
Class 5 was on
innovation organization,

00:02:50.560 --> 00:02:52.600
and we talked about
the different models

00:02:52.600 --> 00:02:58.840
that kind of govern the ideology
of innovation in this country.

00:02:58.840 --> 00:03:00.850
The associationalist
model, which

00:03:00.850 --> 00:03:04.150
we could call the public-private
partnership kind of model.

00:03:04.150 --> 00:03:09.263
The conservative model, which
is governmental intervention.

00:03:09.263 --> 00:03:11.180
Government should stay
away from intervention,

00:03:11.180 --> 00:03:13.090
including into the
innovation system

00:03:13.090 --> 00:03:15.730
except at the most
basic kind of levels

00:03:15.730 --> 00:03:20.410
versus a national security model
which justifies intervention

00:03:20.410 --> 00:03:26.030
at any stage if the need is
related to national security.

00:03:26.030 --> 00:03:27.085
And these debates go on.

00:03:27.085 --> 00:03:28.460
There's a couple
of other models,

00:03:28.460 --> 00:03:29.877
but those are the
ones that really

00:03:29.877 --> 00:03:33.040
represent the core
debates that still go on.

00:03:33.040 --> 00:03:35.650
We talked about the importance
of looking at innovation

00:03:35.650 --> 00:03:38.560
from both the institutional
and the personal level.

00:03:38.560 --> 00:03:40.830
So people innovate,
institutions don't.

00:03:40.830 --> 00:03:43.870
You need to understand how
the institutions interact.

00:03:43.870 --> 00:03:48.490
But in the end, people
own particular innovations

00:03:48.490 --> 00:03:49.500
and bring them about.

00:03:49.500 --> 00:03:51.083
So you've got to
understand innovation

00:03:51.083 --> 00:03:53.440
at that personal level, as well.

00:03:53.440 --> 00:03:59.440
We talked about Donald
Stokes and a core issue

00:03:59.440 --> 00:04:02.530
in the US system, its
disconnected model.

00:04:02.530 --> 00:04:05.620
The fact that we tend to
focus on early stage research

00:04:05.620 --> 00:04:07.660
and have less focus
on the implementation

00:04:07.660 --> 00:04:09.490
stages further along.

00:04:09.490 --> 00:04:12.850
And that creates a significant
tech transition problem

00:04:12.850 --> 00:04:14.340
in the US system.

00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:17.529
Class 6 was about that how
to get across this, quote,

00:04:17.529 --> 00:04:20.709
"Valley of Death," which
has been the major policy

00:04:20.709 --> 00:04:24.010
preoccupation of US
science and technology

00:04:24.010 --> 00:04:27.590
policy for the
last say 25 years.

00:04:27.590 --> 00:04:31.150
And in contrast we read
Vernon Ruttan, another growth

00:04:31.150 --> 00:04:36.290
economist, who taught
us that, by the way,

00:04:36.290 --> 00:04:38.680
there's a whole parallel
system out there,

00:04:38.680 --> 00:04:41.370
there's a parallel universe
in the way in which the US R&D

00:04:41.370 --> 00:04:42.370
systems are organized.

00:04:42.370 --> 00:04:45.350
There's a highly connected
defense information system

00:04:45.350 --> 00:04:49.180
that's very different than
the somewhat disconnected

00:04:49.180 --> 00:04:51.760
civilian side R&D system.

00:04:51.760 --> 00:04:56.050
Class 7 was great group theory,
what does innovation look

00:04:56.050 --> 00:04:58.720
like at the face to face level?

00:04:58.720 --> 00:05:01.690
Innovation, again, is people,
it's not institutions.

00:05:01.690 --> 00:05:03.550
And what are the
rules sets that tend

00:05:03.550 --> 00:05:06.940
to govern the way in which
teams and groups of people

00:05:06.940 --> 00:05:09.100
working on complex innovations.

00:05:09.100 --> 00:05:10.120
How they come together?

00:05:10.120 --> 00:05:11.140
How do they assemble?

00:05:11.140 --> 00:05:12.190
How do they organize?

00:05:12.190 --> 00:05:14.230
What are their rules?

00:05:14.230 --> 00:05:17.770
So that's all about a
third direct innovation

00:05:17.770 --> 00:05:20.880
factor, innovation organization,
at both face to face

00:05:20.880 --> 00:05:22.780
and institutional levels.

00:05:22.780 --> 00:05:25.750
Class 8 was around DARPA
as a very different kind

00:05:25.750 --> 00:05:32.530
of model that attempts to
do both a connected model

00:05:32.530 --> 00:05:34.540
and innovation through
a connected model

00:05:34.540 --> 00:05:36.610
at the institutional
level, but it also

00:05:36.610 --> 00:05:39.040
operates in creating great
groups in a very conscious kind

00:05:39.040 --> 00:05:39.540
of way.

00:05:39.540 --> 00:05:41.290
And we explored the whole idea--

00:05:41.290 --> 00:05:45.490
revolution role
that DARPA played.

00:05:45.490 --> 00:05:49.750
Class 9 last week was
really about the challenges

00:05:49.750 --> 00:05:52.510
in the health innovation system.

00:05:52.510 --> 00:06:00.790
It's a early stage research,
basic research focused system.

00:06:00.790 --> 00:06:04.750
It's a quite disconnected model,
big organizational challenges

00:06:04.750 --> 00:06:07.150
through the 27
different institutes

00:06:07.150 --> 00:06:11.500
and centers at the National
Institutes of Health.

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:14.350
Getting cross-cutting science
going between those institutes

00:06:14.350 --> 00:06:16.840
is hard.

00:06:16.840 --> 00:06:22.840
Yet we're now at a stage where a
new revolution is coming along,

00:06:22.840 --> 00:06:26.350
which some termed the
convergence revolution.

00:06:26.350 --> 00:06:29.528
That's going to mandate much
more cross-cutting science,

00:06:29.528 --> 00:06:31.570
and yet we've got an
institutional organizational

00:06:31.570 --> 00:06:34.300
problem that's not
adapted to handling

00:06:34.300 --> 00:06:38.620
the kind of next generation
breakthrough territories.

00:06:38.620 --> 00:06:43.060
And now, energy.

00:06:43.060 --> 00:06:49.840
So we're going to really bring
to bear here the legacy sector

00:06:49.840 --> 00:06:53.680
analysis model that we've been
touching on at several points.

00:06:53.680 --> 00:06:55.660
But today it really
comes into focus.

00:06:55.660 --> 00:06:58.960
Obviously, we touched on it last
week in the context of the NIH,

00:06:58.960 --> 00:07:01.450
but it really
comes to bear here.

00:07:01.450 --> 00:07:04.900
And the issue of innovating
in complex established sectors

00:07:04.900 --> 00:07:07.300
is a big problem for the US.

00:07:07.300 --> 00:07:10.730
It's a problem for everybody,
it's a particular problem here.

00:07:10.730 --> 00:07:13.600
If we can get around
and tackle this problem

00:07:13.600 --> 00:07:16.120
we could address
a lot of issues.

00:07:16.120 --> 00:07:21.880
Since 80% of the economy
is in these legacy sectors,

00:07:21.880 --> 00:07:25.660
we limit our growth
rate by essentially

00:07:25.660 --> 00:07:29.680
doing a new frontier kind of
innovation model of looking

00:07:29.680 --> 00:07:31.870
at standing up the
next big thing,

00:07:31.870 --> 00:07:34.120
we lose track of what
we've done in the past,

00:07:34.120 --> 00:07:39.040
we tend to focus our innovation
on standing up new territories.

00:07:39.040 --> 00:07:41.390
That affects our
growth rate, right?

00:07:41.390 --> 00:07:45.190
So the whole IT sector
in the United States,

00:07:45.190 --> 00:07:49.150
as huge as it is, is still
measured as only about 4.6%

00:07:49.150 --> 00:07:51.360
of the US economy.

00:07:51.360 --> 00:07:53.940
That includes copper
wire telephones

00:07:53.940 --> 00:07:56.250
and hard bound
books, too, right?

00:07:56.250 --> 00:07:57.995
In that information
technology sector.

00:08:03.400 --> 00:08:07.540
It's a challenging
issue of how to bring

00:08:07.540 --> 00:08:08.875
innovation of the sectors.

00:08:08.875 --> 00:08:10.750
If we could figure out
a better way to do it,

00:08:10.750 --> 00:08:13.960
if innovation is the dominant
causative factor of growth,

00:08:13.960 --> 00:08:16.090
then we start to think
about affecting our growth

00:08:16.090 --> 00:08:17.300
rate in a new kind of way.

00:08:17.300 --> 00:08:21.130
So that's why this
case study, I think,

00:08:21.130 --> 00:08:24.310
is particularly significant, not
only for energy itself, which

00:08:24.310 --> 00:08:28.120
is obviously very important, but
for its implications of how do

00:08:28.120 --> 00:08:31.330
we innovate in legacy sectors.

00:08:31.330 --> 00:08:33.610
So we'll start with
Socolow and Pacala.

00:08:33.610 --> 00:08:35.789
And who's got
Socolow and Pacala?

00:08:35.789 --> 00:08:36.340
Matthew?

00:08:36.340 --> 00:08:37.419
All right.

00:08:37.419 --> 00:08:42.190
I'll just briefly
summarize their work.

00:08:42.190 --> 00:08:48.610
As you know, both
Princeton experts,

00:08:48.610 --> 00:08:52.900
they helped give us a
conceptual framework

00:08:52.900 --> 00:08:59.590
for thinking about the challenge
coming up in energy technology.

00:08:59.590 --> 00:09:03.100
And the community
have been doing

00:09:03.100 --> 00:09:05.162
a lot of fairly sloppy
thinking about-- everybody

00:09:05.162 --> 00:09:07.120
had their favorite silver
bullet that was going

00:09:07.120 --> 00:09:09.640
to solve all problems, right?

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:13.145
And Socolow and Pacala got us
thinking that, gee, there's

00:09:13.145 --> 00:09:14.770
not going to be a
single silver bullet,

00:09:14.770 --> 00:09:17.290
there's going to be a
whole series of things that

00:09:17.290 --> 00:09:21.700
need to be undertaken if we're
going to tackle the energy

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:23.720
technology challenge.

00:09:23.720 --> 00:09:25.690
And so they developed
something which is now

00:09:25.690 --> 00:09:28.753
widely known as wedges theory.

00:09:28.753 --> 00:09:29.920
And when they were writing--

00:09:33.900 --> 00:09:39.360
if we just stabilized
CO2 and greenhouse gases,

00:09:39.360 --> 00:09:42.900
at the time they were writing,
that would have been enough.

00:09:42.900 --> 00:09:45.390
We now know that we've got
to go much more deeply.

00:09:45.390 --> 00:09:49.590
So it complicates this
wedges story significantly.

00:09:49.590 --> 00:09:52.860
But when they were
writing, as you can see,

00:09:52.860 --> 00:09:55.890
their assumption was
that would be the growth

00:09:55.890 --> 00:09:58.860
curve of greenhouse
gases and we could simply

00:09:58.860 --> 00:10:02.438
stabilize it by introducing
these wedges, that

00:10:02.438 --> 00:10:03.480
could tackle the problem.

00:10:06.690 --> 00:10:09.150
When they put this
out in 2004, it really

00:10:09.150 --> 00:10:10.930
gave everyone a new
kind of picture,

00:10:10.930 --> 00:10:13.020
a new kind of
intellectual framework

00:10:13.020 --> 00:10:16.680
to help think about
this big energy problem.

00:10:16.680 --> 00:10:19.800
They picked 15 different
energy initiatives,

00:10:19.800 --> 00:10:22.530
they argued that if you
did any seven of them

00:10:22.530 --> 00:10:26.030
you could grow them in a
reasonable time frame into--

00:10:26.030 --> 00:10:28.710
that multi decade time frame
into large enough wedges

00:10:28.710 --> 00:10:31.680
of energy supply that you
could bring emissions down

00:10:31.680 --> 00:10:36.120
over a five-decade period
to a stabilized 2005.

00:10:36.120 --> 00:10:40.040
So we now we've got an
80% reduction, not just

00:10:40.040 --> 00:10:41.460
stabilization.

00:10:41.460 --> 00:10:44.700
But the concept
is still with us.

00:10:44.700 --> 00:10:47.910
Now, some of these
wedges were clearly

00:10:47.910 --> 00:10:52.830
within the range of adoption,
and with a concerted effort

00:10:52.830 --> 00:10:55.860
they could be scaled up
in a timely kind of way.

00:10:55.860 --> 00:10:59.610
Others were just plain
really hard to even think

00:10:59.610 --> 00:11:01.230
about implementing.

00:11:01.230 --> 00:11:06.810
For example, they called
for massive deforestation.

00:11:06.810 --> 00:11:09.730
A big challenge in countries
where that would need to occur.

00:11:09.730 --> 00:11:12.630
They called for a 50%
reduction in driving

00:11:12.630 --> 00:11:15.010
by 2 billion vehicles.

00:11:15.010 --> 00:11:15.510
Yeah.

00:11:15.510 --> 00:11:18.430
Good luck.

00:11:18.430 --> 00:11:21.420
You know, massive adoption
of conservation tillage.

00:11:21.420 --> 00:11:23.850
I mean, all these are
conceivable, right?

00:11:23.850 --> 00:11:26.890
But some are harder than others.

00:11:26.890 --> 00:11:29.300
And they take not only
changes in government

00:11:29.300 --> 00:11:31.740
to write to policy and
technology advance,

00:11:31.740 --> 00:11:34.660
they require very significant
behavioral challenges,

00:11:34.660 --> 00:11:38.850
which is particularly
difficult to impose.

00:11:38.850 --> 00:11:43.560
And others, like carbon capture
and sequestration technology,

00:11:43.560 --> 00:11:48.240
are still, to this day, a
considerable time period away

00:11:48.240 --> 00:11:50.400
from practical implementation.

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:53.550
We don't have the
right technologies yet.

00:11:53.550 --> 00:11:55.872
And then there's a whole
period of development

00:11:55.872 --> 00:11:57.330
and demonstration
that really needs

00:11:57.330 --> 00:12:00.640
to be ongoing
before we can really

00:12:00.640 --> 00:12:02.370
implement those approaches.

00:12:02.370 --> 00:12:04.870
We just don't know what the
best practices are, particularly

00:12:04.870 --> 00:12:06.790
in the sequestration side.

00:12:06.790 --> 00:12:10.060
So that's some of
the challenges here.

00:12:10.060 --> 00:12:14.410
Interestingly, Socolow
and Pacala's work

00:12:14.410 --> 00:12:18.490
got taken up by the contending
communities battling

00:12:18.490 --> 00:12:22.630
over climate change
at that time.

00:12:22.630 --> 00:12:24.760
So Socolow and
Pacala, again, they're

00:12:24.760 --> 00:12:27.160
only battling for
a 50% reduction--

00:12:27.160 --> 00:12:30.850
I mean, excuse me, they're
battling for stabilization, not

00:12:30.850 --> 00:12:33.580
a 50% or 80% reduction.

00:12:33.580 --> 00:12:36.040
They argued that we
could get their wedges

00:12:36.040 --> 00:12:38.680
without doing a lot of
breakthrough work, right?

00:12:38.680 --> 00:12:40.870
That the solutions were at hand.

00:12:40.870 --> 00:12:44.757
So the environmental community
was facing a big battle

00:12:44.757 --> 00:12:45.340
with industry.

00:12:45.340 --> 00:12:49.880
And the industry was saying,
sure, we'll do climate change,

00:12:49.880 --> 00:12:52.240
see in 20 years we're
going to do some R&D

00:12:52.240 --> 00:12:55.330
and we should have it done
within at least 20-year period,

00:12:55.330 --> 00:12:56.500
no problem.

00:12:56.500 --> 00:12:58.210
So that was obviously
unacceptable

00:12:58.210 --> 00:13:00.070
to the environmental community.

00:13:00.070 --> 00:13:03.070
They used Socolow and Pacala
to argue, wait a minute,

00:13:03.070 --> 00:13:05.950
we don't need to do these
fundamental breakthroughs,

00:13:05.950 --> 00:13:08.890
the solutions are at hand.

00:13:08.890 --> 00:13:12.670
So in effect it
pulled both sides off

00:13:12.670 --> 00:13:17.110
of technology
development, right?

00:13:17.110 --> 00:13:19.090
In a period of time
where we actually really

00:13:19.090 --> 00:13:21.010
needed to do a lot of
technology development

00:13:21.010 --> 00:13:22.843
because I would argue
with you that if we're

00:13:22.843 --> 00:13:25.870
going to get to the
levels of CO2 reductions

00:13:25.870 --> 00:13:30.270
that we need to reach, there
is a lot of technology advance

00:13:30.270 --> 00:13:31.690
that needs to go on.

00:13:31.690 --> 00:13:34.420
And this kind of pulled
the debate out of that.

00:13:34.420 --> 00:13:38.950
It's not their fault, that's
not what they intended at all,

00:13:38.950 --> 00:13:46.487
but it created a kind
of positive agenda

00:13:46.487 --> 00:13:48.070
for the environmental
committee that I

00:13:48.070 --> 00:13:53.500
think in the end was misleading
to them as well as to others.

00:13:53.500 --> 00:13:55.630
So that was the dilemma
in what they proposed,

00:13:55.630 --> 00:13:57.970
but nonetheless
this wedges concept

00:13:57.970 --> 00:14:01.800
presents a picture of how we're
going to go after this problem.

00:14:01.800 --> 00:14:04.090
That remains
extremely important.

00:14:04.090 --> 00:14:07.330
Matt, it's all yours.

