00:28:34.440 --> 00:28:36.285
So we're now going
to dive into--

00:28:41.060 --> 00:28:44.690
Chuck Weiss and I affected
a whole book on this.

00:28:44.690 --> 00:28:54.110
This is just a kind of
snapshot, but the idea

00:28:54.110 --> 00:28:58.660
we tried to get across here is
that challenge is big enough

00:28:58.660 --> 00:29:01.730
that we're going to have to get
inside the kind of black box

00:29:01.730 --> 00:29:05.480
of innovation, innovation
policy, innovation proposition.

00:29:05.480 --> 00:29:09.740
So there'd been a lot of
articles around the time we

00:29:09.740 --> 00:29:13.010
worked on this, 2009 timetable.

00:29:13.010 --> 00:29:16.040
And a lot of major
studies, and the studies

00:29:16.040 --> 00:29:21.610
always said, and we're going to
need some technology advances,

00:29:21.610 --> 00:29:23.840
let's do a lot of R&D, right?

00:29:23.840 --> 00:29:26.900
And that's kind of
as far as they went.

00:29:26.900 --> 00:29:31.910
And what we were attempting
to do in the book, as well

00:29:31.910 --> 00:29:36.500
as pieces that came out of it,
like what I had you all read,

00:29:36.500 --> 00:29:43.130
was really dig into how that
innovation system worked

00:29:43.130 --> 00:29:47.650
and understand it in a more
coherent and real kind of way,

00:29:47.650 --> 00:29:51.380
getting us in there to that
black box of innovation policy

00:29:51.380 --> 00:29:53.450
and figure out
what could be done.

00:29:53.450 --> 00:29:58.760
Just as a few background points,
historically, the government

00:29:58.760 --> 00:30:00.650
has been much more
interventionist

00:30:00.650 --> 00:30:04.160
in the energy sector than
most other sectors, right?

00:30:04.160 --> 00:30:07.280
Government is historically very
interventionist in the health

00:30:07.280 --> 00:30:10.250
sector, it's been very
interventionist in the energy

00:30:10.250 --> 00:30:11.990
sector as well.

00:30:11.990 --> 00:30:13.970
And the political
parties tend to have

00:30:13.970 --> 00:30:18.590
their favorite
technologies, which

00:30:18.590 --> 00:30:22.730
complicates the political agenda
here for a technology agenda.

00:30:22.730 --> 00:30:25.160
It will complicate it for the
next several years for sure.

00:30:25.160 --> 00:30:28.160
We're already seeing
some of those slides.

00:30:28.160 --> 00:30:31.280
And then there's
another reality here,

00:30:31.280 --> 00:30:38.050
which is we don't have a
lot of the technologies we

00:30:38.050 --> 00:30:40.240
need at hand yet.

00:30:40.240 --> 00:30:45.910
There's still a very significant
technology development effort

00:30:45.910 --> 00:30:48.550
that needs to go on and a
series of these really important

00:30:48.550 --> 00:30:49.270
strands.

00:30:49.270 --> 00:30:51.998
We can see what
the pathways are,

00:30:51.998 --> 00:30:54.040
but a lot of the technologies
we're going to need

00:30:54.040 --> 00:30:55.960
are still not
technology ready, much

00:30:55.960 --> 00:30:58.180
less being economically
ready, where

00:30:58.180 --> 00:31:00.250
it's ready for market adoption.

00:31:00.250 --> 00:31:05.320
So that complicates this
challenge very significant.

00:31:05.320 --> 00:31:07.810
Energy is scale, right?

00:31:07.810 --> 00:31:10.540
It is a gigantic sector.

00:31:10.540 --> 00:31:14.582
And you can't
consider energy policy

00:31:14.582 --> 00:31:15.915
unless you're considering scale.

00:31:18.780 --> 00:31:21.540
There is a technological,
economic, political, social

00:31:21.540 --> 00:31:28.170
paradigm that creates barriers
to change in the energy sector

00:31:28.170 --> 00:31:30.090
that are quite significant.

00:31:30.090 --> 00:31:33.090
Private sector R&D,
and obviously this

00:31:33.090 --> 00:31:34.500
is private sector technology.

00:31:34.500 --> 00:31:36.865
The government is not in
control of this technology

00:31:36.865 --> 00:31:38.640
to say the least.

00:31:38.640 --> 00:31:42.450
Private sector R&D is
discouraged by wild price

00:31:42.450 --> 00:31:45.150
oscillations in energy markets.

00:31:45.150 --> 00:31:48.820
We'll look at some of
those in just a minute.

00:31:48.820 --> 00:31:54.660
$20 a barrel in 1998, $140 a
barrel in 2008, $35 a barrel

00:31:54.660 --> 00:31:57.600
in 2016.

00:31:57.600 --> 00:32:01.440
It's very hard to do R&D
against those kinds of price

00:32:01.440 --> 00:32:03.390
disruptions.

00:32:03.390 --> 00:32:07.380
The public sector has
been working on energy R&D

00:32:07.380 --> 00:32:11.040
and comparatively few
technologies have transitioned.

00:32:11.040 --> 00:32:14.295
Again, fracking frankly is the
major technology development

00:32:14.295 --> 00:32:17.460
that really has transitioned.

00:32:17.460 --> 00:32:20.610
And you've got to think
about parallel and supporting

00:32:20.610 --> 00:32:24.390
policies, not only on
technology, but also on price.

00:32:24.390 --> 00:32:25.200
Right?

00:32:25.200 --> 00:32:28.290
So it's technology, supply,
but that's dramatically

00:32:28.290 --> 00:32:30.150
affected by pricing.

00:32:30.150 --> 00:32:34.270
So very large in
scale and scope.

00:32:34.270 --> 00:32:36.420
The problem of energy,
as I said before,

00:32:36.420 --> 00:32:39.030
really is the problem of scale.

00:32:39.030 --> 00:32:41.880
You can think about a large
scale kind of activity,

00:32:41.880 --> 00:32:45.990
like an Apollo type
project for pursuing this,

00:32:45.990 --> 00:32:50.580
but you would not have an
Apollo type project that's

00:32:50.580 --> 00:32:53.460
government contract-led, right?

00:32:53.460 --> 00:32:56.950
We're not going to solve this
except in the private sector,

00:32:56.950 --> 00:33:00.300
which makes the effort
considerably more complicated.

00:33:00.300 --> 00:33:02.895
And as Socolow and
Pacala suggested to us

00:33:02.895 --> 00:33:04.270
in the reading we
just discussed,

00:33:04.270 --> 00:33:07.540
this is a 50 year project.

00:33:07.540 --> 00:33:09.960
So the United States has never
done a 50 year technology

00:33:09.960 --> 00:33:11.400
project.

00:33:11.400 --> 00:33:14.580
We're lucky if we do three year
technology projects these days.

00:33:14.580 --> 00:33:17.610
Apollo was a nine
year project, right?

00:33:17.610 --> 00:33:20.970
That's about as long
as we can stand, much

00:33:20.970 --> 00:33:22.590
less a multi-decade problem.

00:33:22.590 --> 00:33:24.430
And then, with a
multi-decade problem,

00:33:24.430 --> 00:33:27.720
we run the problem of
locking in prematurely

00:33:27.720 --> 00:33:30.000
to wrong technologies.

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:32.790
So that's the
fundamental problem

00:33:32.790 --> 00:33:36.820
with corn-based ethanol,
which 1970s already

00:33:36.820 --> 00:33:39.870
felt like, great, corn-based
ethanol, what could be better?

00:33:39.870 --> 00:33:44.130
Farmers get rich, they grow
our energy for us, how nice.

00:33:44.130 --> 00:33:48.660
But it turned out to be not
as significant emissions

00:33:48.660 --> 00:33:50.970
reduction, if anything,
maybe the opposite.

00:33:50.970 --> 00:33:52.440
So locking in.

00:33:52.440 --> 00:33:56.610
We're now every bit as addicted
to corn as we are to oil,

00:33:56.610 --> 00:34:00.270
and locking in prematurely on
a technology is a big problem.

00:34:00.270 --> 00:34:04.260
How do you maintain a certain
amount of technology neutrality

00:34:04.260 --> 00:34:05.640
over a 40 year period?

00:34:05.640 --> 00:34:09.600
We have never tried anything
as complicated as that before.

00:34:09.600 --> 00:34:12.929
And arguably, you need to
organize around barriers

00:34:12.929 --> 00:34:18.940
to market launch, not just
throw R&D money at the problem.

00:34:18.940 --> 00:34:20.280
So we'll get into all of that.

00:34:20.280 --> 00:34:24.330
But energy arguably requires
a new unified theory

00:34:24.330 --> 00:34:29.070
of innovation because it
is such a complex project.

00:34:29.070 --> 00:34:31.469
You can't just do
a pipeline model,

00:34:31.469 --> 00:34:34.000
you can't just do in an
induced innovation model,

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:35.430
you can't just do
a manufacturing

00:34:35.430 --> 00:34:38.100
led innovation model.

00:34:38.100 --> 00:34:40.560
You've got to think much more
deeply about how you bring

00:34:40.560 --> 00:34:44.400
all these models to bear using
an innovation organization

00:34:44.400 --> 00:34:45.889
approach.

00:34:45.889 --> 00:34:49.320
It's kind of no way of getting
out of that box in the energy

00:34:49.320 --> 00:34:50.210
sector.

00:34:50.210 --> 00:34:50.909
AUDIENCE: Is there
a paper that's

00:34:50.909 --> 00:34:52.570
looking to pass
energy revolutions

00:34:52.570 --> 00:34:57.762
and figure out like the
main kind of pushers?

00:34:57.762 --> 00:34:59.970
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Well,
we went on too many, right?

00:34:59.970 --> 00:35:03.120
So I don't know how
many million years it

00:35:03.120 --> 00:35:05.460
took, but we did wood fire.

00:35:05.460 --> 00:35:06.300
We did that.

00:35:06.300 --> 00:35:09.030
That was big.

00:35:09.030 --> 00:35:12.600
Then, from wood we did coal.

00:35:12.600 --> 00:35:16.290
And [INAUDIBLE] tells the story
that William Barton Rogers,

00:35:16.290 --> 00:35:19.860
the esteemed first
president, and frankly,

00:35:19.860 --> 00:35:29.100
genius behind the MIT
model, he died on the podium

00:35:29.100 --> 00:35:33.060
