00:35:42.990 --> 00:35:47.940
In a remarkably quick period
of time, you know 60, 70 years,

00:35:47.940 --> 00:35:49.630
we actually moved to oil.

00:35:49.630 --> 00:35:50.130
Right?

00:35:50.130 --> 00:35:52.350
That was remarkably quick.

00:35:54.930 --> 00:35:58.320
And you know we've been on
that fossil fuel revolution

00:35:58.320 --> 00:35:59.490
ever since.

00:35:59.490 --> 00:36:03.360
And it's not easy
to shift, so these

00:36:03.360 --> 00:36:07.230
are very long-term projects.

00:36:07.230 --> 00:36:09.270
And you really have
to think about time

00:36:09.270 --> 00:36:14.400
and scale over and over again
when we think about undertaking

00:36:14.400 --> 00:36:15.750
energy technology change.

00:36:18.480 --> 00:36:20.400
So we talked about
some of the models

00:36:20.400 --> 00:36:23.880
previously just to remind you
we know the pipeline model well.

00:36:23.880 --> 00:36:25.980
For sure there is going
to be a profound need here

00:36:25.980 --> 00:36:29.390
for breakthrough research.

00:36:29.390 --> 00:36:33.300
There is a big valley of death
problem in that pipeline model

00:36:33.300 --> 00:36:35.347
that we've got to
think very hard about.

00:36:35.347 --> 00:36:36.930
But that's not the
only problem, we've

00:36:36.930 --> 00:36:38.855
got induced innovation here.

00:36:38.855 --> 00:36:40.230
In other words,
industry is going

00:36:40.230 --> 00:36:43.140
they have to take responsibility
for a lot of these particularly

00:36:43.140 --> 00:36:44.580
incremental advances.

00:36:44.580 --> 00:36:46.050
But how do you
encourage that when

00:36:46.050 --> 00:36:48.810
the industry is locked
into a set of technologies

00:36:48.810 --> 00:36:51.300
that you want to mitigate?

00:36:51.300 --> 00:36:54.180
That really complicates the
induced innovation model.

00:36:54.180 --> 00:36:56.120
Well, it was in the article.

00:36:56.120 --> 00:36:58.320
Chuck and I've been
thinking since then

00:36:58.320 --> 00:37:00.510
because from the book
there's an extended pipeline

00:37:00.510 --> 00:37:02.370
model, the whole defense
sector model where

00:37:02.370 --> 00:37:05.370
the government engages not
just at the upfront stages,

00:37:05.370 --> 00:37:08.670
but the later stages through
implementation as well.

00:37:08.670 --> 00:37:10.080
What can we use in that model?

00:37:10.080 --> 00:37:11.940
And that's a Defense
Department-owned model

00:37:11.940 --> 00:37:12.910
by and large.

00:37:12.910 --> 00:37:15.800
And we'll talk later when we
talk about the Dorothy Rubin

00:37:15.800 --> 00:37:18.270
reading about whether
that's applied.

00:37:18.270 --> 00:37:19.195
Manufacturing led.

00:37:19.195 --> 00:37:20.820
In other words, we're
not going to have

00:37:20.820 --> 00:37:23.710
carbon pricing for a
significant period of time.

00:37:23.710 --> 00:37:26.220
So unless you drive
the price down,

00:37:26.220 --> 00:37:29.080
these technologies
will never enter.

00:37:29.080 --> 00:37:31.350
So the way you
drive price down is

00:37:31.350 --> 00:37:34.200
through manufacturing
advances and process advances

00:37:34.200 --> 00:37:36.300
and that becomes very
much part of what

00:37:36.300 --> 00:37:39.150
you've got to consider in
an energy innovation model

00:37:39.150 --> 00:37:40.150
as well.

00:37:40.150 --> 00:37:41.760
So innovation organization.

00:37:41.760 --> 00:37:44.130
How do you put these
complex pieces together

00:37:44.130 --> 00:37:47.910
for a new model is really
at the core of this.

00:37:47.910 --> 00:37:51.630
So just to summarize so far,
it's a problem of scale,

00:37:51.630 --> 00:37:53.490
we're up against a
technological, economic,

00:37:53.490 --> 00:37:55.970
political, social paradigm--
we'll talk about that

00:37:55.970 --> 00:37:56.820
in a minute--

00:37:56.820 --> 00:38:00.420
in a very complex
established legacy sector.

00:38:00.420 --> 00:38:02.790
And maintaining
technology neutrality

00:38:02.790 --> 00:38:06.390
over a 50 year period, a
really critical problem,

00:38:06.390 --> 00:38:09.840
which needs a tremendous amount
of thought and organizing.

00:38:09.840 --> 00:38:13.140
And then we've got to
undertake the integration

00:38:13.140 --> 00:38:16.170
of the different models by
which the dynamics of innovation

00:38:16.170 --> 00:38:17.790
get played out, right?

00:38:17.790 --> 00:38:20.100
You can't just do pipeline
here, you can't just

00:38:20.100 --> 00:38:22.645
do extended pipeline.

00:38:22.645 --> 00:38:24.270
You've got to really
bring all of these

00:38:24.270 --> 00:38:27.250
to bear because they're
all part of that solution.

00:38:27.250 --> 00:38:31.110
So innovation organization
becomes central here

00:38:31.110 --> 00:38:35.100
to an energy
technology revolution.

00:38:35.100 --> 00:38:37.680
Let's look at
investments in energy.

