00:39:47.320 --> 00:39:51.460
project for them and they had to
keep investing in R&D to do it.

00:39:51.460 --> 00:39:54.820
The pharmaceutical
sector invests 18%

00:39:54.820 --> 00:39:56.850
because their drug
terms keep running out.

00:39:56.850 --> 00:39:59.800
They've got to stay on
top of the R&D side.

00:39:59.800 --> 00:40:02.680
The biotech sector invests 39%.

00:40:02.680 --> 00:40:04.780
That may be a little
unfair comparison

00:40:04.780 --> 00:40:07.360
because a lot of
the biotech industry

00:40:07.360 --> 00:40:10.210
has no revenues at all, so it
may skew the numbers a bit.

00:40:10.210 --> 00:40:13.000
But the other two are
probably pretty good signals.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:14.200
Established industry.

00:40:14.200 --> 00:40:16.330
The electronics
industry, 8% of sales.

00:40:16.330 --> 00:40:19.720
The auto industry, at least
before the great recession,

00:40:19.720 --> 00:40:22.810
was around 3% to
3 and 1/2 percent

00:40:22.810 --> 00:40:27.725
of annual revenues in R&D.
Those are pretty mature sectors.

00:40:30.590 --> 00:40:35.540
Average R&D to annual revenues
for all of US industry is 2.6%.

00:40:35.540 --> 00:40:37.880
That includes dry
cleaners, right?

00:40:37.880 --> 00:40:41.120
That's everybody, that's all in.

00:40:41.120 --> 00:40:46.580
Private energy R&D as
a percentage of R&D--

00:40:46.580 --> 00:40:51.872
R&D as a percentage of annual
revenues is less than 1%.

00:40:51.872 --> 00:40:54.860
How are we going to do this?

00:40:54.860 --> 00:40:57.440
And this does not--

00:40:57.440 --> 00:40:59.580
this is not good, right?

00:40:59.580 --> 00:41:02.670
Now, why is it so low
in the energy sector?

00:41:02.670 --> 00:41:06.040
Well, part of the story is that
the revenues are so enormous,

00:41:06.040 --> 00:41:06.540
right?

00:41:06.540 --> 00:41:11.760
This is a powerful
revenue-generating sector.

00:41:11.760 --> 00:41:16.840
So that's part of it, but
it's not a full explanation.

00:41:16.840 --> 00:41:19.050
This is a sector that's
got an economic model

00:41:19.050 --> 00:41:22.560
and it's sustaining
that model, and it's not

00:41:22.560 --> 00:41:25.320
all that interested
in diversification

00:41:25.320 --> 00:41:30.920
from what's an extremely
successful set of approaches.

00:41:30.920 --> 00:41:35.810
Now, let's say we up
the federal R&D, right?

00:41:35.810 --> 00:41:38.070
To kind of offset not a
terribly pretty picture

00:41:38.070 --> 00:41:39.500
on the private sector R&D side.

00:41:43.940 --> 00:41:46.910
When the feds really
want to do something big,

00:41:46.910 --> 00:41:49.190
what kind of money
do they spend it on?

00:41:49.190 --> 00:41:51.020
The Apollo program,
over nine years-- now,

00:41:51.020 --> 00:41:52.820
this is both R&D
and implementation.

00:41:52.820 --> 00:41:58.580
That was $185 billion in 2002
dollars over that nine year

00:41:58.580 --> 00:42:00.020
period.

00:42:00.020 --> 00:42:03.050
Carter-Reagan defense
buildup, right?

00:42:03.050 --> 00:42:06.530
That got us know all the
stuff we read about in DARPA,

00:42:06.530 --> 00:42:10.700
precision, stealth,
UAVs, submarines

00:42:10.700 --> 00:42:14.180
that nobody likes to talk
about, a bunch of fancy stuff.

00:42:14.180 --> 00:42:17.600
That was $445 billion
over eight years.

00:42:17.600 --> 00:42:21.650
Doubling NIH was $138
billion over five years.

00:42:21.650 --> 00:42:23.480
The ballistic missile
defense program,

00:42:23.480 --> 00:42:27.080
which until fairly recently
was the largest technology

00:42:27.080 --> 00:42:29.500
initiative the government had
going, its first six years

00:42:29.500 --> 00:42:32.580
was $145 billion.

00:42:32.580 --> 00:42:34.580
That's what the government
spends when it really

00:42:34.580 --> 00:42:37.760
wants to get technology done.

00:42:37.760 --> 00:42:39.670
It's not spending
this on energy.

00:42:39.670 --> 00:42:40.170
OK?

00:42:40.170 --> 00:42:41.253
We're not at those levels.

00:42:43.660 --> 00:42:51.310
Interestingly, this is energy
in R&D spending compared

00:42:51.310 --> 00:42:52.930
to the price of crude oil.

00:42:52.930 --> 00:42:57.570
And you can see the remarkable
similarities in these lines,

00:42:57.570 --> 00:42:58.600
right?

00:42:58.600 --> 00:43:01.180
Price of oil goes up,
let's throw some R&D at it.

00:43:01.180 --> 00:43:04.060
Price of oil goes down,
pull that R&D back, right?

00:43:04.060 --> 00:43:07.987
You can't run an R&D program
with sustained results on kind

00:43:07.987 --> 00:43:09.070
of a roller coaster model.

00:43:09.070 --> 00:43:10.240
It just doesn't work.

00:43:13.077 --> 00:43:15.160
This story is not just
true for the United States.

00:43:15.160 --> 00:43:19.680
These are all the developed
countries, the OECD countries.

00:43:19.680 --> 00:43:22.570
You can see a high
watermark about 1980

00:43:22.570 --> 00:43:24.838
and similarly coming down
to less than half of that.

00:43:24.838 --> 00:43:26.380
The black line is
the one to look at.

00:43:29.560 --> 00:43:31.210
The International
Energy Agency--

00:43:31.210 --> 00:43:33.810
which is the energy arm
of the OECD countries,

00:43:33.810 --> 00:43:36.520
a highly respected
data collection,

00:43:36.520 --> 00:43:39.700
energy analytical crew--

00:43:39.700 --> 00:43:42.250
in 2008 they did a
major study and they

00:43:42.250 --> 00:43:44.380
concluded that
reducing emissions

00:43:44.380 --> 00:43:50.550
to 50% below 2005 levels.

00:43:50.550 --> 00:43:53.910
When they added up the R&D
as well as the technology

00:43:53.910 --> 00:43:56.100
implementation that
need to be undertaken,

00:43:56.100 --> 00:44:01.260
they estimated that
at a $45 trillion

00:44:01.260 --> 00:44:09.210
project over a 50 year period,
about $1.1 trillion worldwide,

00:44:09.210 --> 00:44:14.580
$1.1 trillion per year
in R&D implementation.

00:44:14.580 --> 00:44:17.790
So, you know, that
number may be way off.

00:44:17.790 --> 00:44:20.070
They were guesstimating, we
got to do this much solar,

00:44:20.070 --> 00:44:21.600
we got to do this
much wind, we have

00:44:21.600 --> 00:44:23.010
to do this much
advanced nuclear,

00:44:23.010 --> 00:44:26.010
we have to have this much carbon
capture and sequestration.

00:44:26.010 --> 00:44:30.610
They were kind of adding up
what the bill might look like.

00:44:30.610 --> 00:44:32.640
So it could be
significantly off--

00:44:32.640 --> 00:44:35.910
but by the way, even if
it's off by a whole lot,

00:44:35.910 --> 00:44:38.040
we're not in range.

00:44:38.040 --> 00:44:44.220
So so far, we've been
talking about this

00:44:44.220 --> 00:44:47.630
as though it was a problem we
could just shovel money at.

00:44:47.630 --> 00:44:48.130
Right?

00:44:48.130 --> 00:44:51.640
That's we've been talking about
for the last five minutes.

00:44:51.640 --> 00:44:55.480
But everybody in
this class knows

00:44:55.480 --> 00:44:59.140
that innovation and a
complex legacy sector,

00:44:59.140 --> 00:45:03.100
like energy, it's much
more complicated than just

00:45:03.100 --> 00:45:04.700
throwing money at the problem.

00:45:04.700 --> 00:45:08.440
So you've seen
these slides before.

00:45:08.440 --> 00:45:12.460
The US is a covered wagon
technology culture, right?

00:45:12.460 --> 00:45:18.910
We like to leave our old
neighborhoods behind and move

00:45:18.910 --> 00:45:22.030
new technology into
open field new frontier

00:45:22.030 --> 00:45:25.060
kind of innovation, we take
our covered wagons west,

00:45:25.060 --> 00:45:27.130
we go over the mountain,
we settle new technology

00:45:27.130 --> 00:45:28.222
territories.

00:45:28.222 --> 00:45:30.430
That's what we're pretty
good at, we like to do that.

00:45:30.430 --> 00:45:34.270
We're not good at
this problem, right?

00:45:34.270 --> 00:45:37.450
Bringing technology advanced
back into established sectors.

00:45:37.450 --> 00:45:39.490
We don't do this.

00:45:39.490 --> 00:45:42.640
And that technology, as
we've discussed before,

00:45:42.640 --> 00:45:44.003
it has to parachute in.

00:45:44.003 --> 00:45:45.670
And by the way, the
incumbents are going

00:45:45.670 --> 00:45:48.110
to shoot at it on the way down.

00:45:48.110 --> 00:45:51.370
So it's not just a matter
of throwing R&D money

00:45:51.370 --> 00:45:52.210
at this problem.

00:45:52.210 --> 00:45:55.180
We've got a much
bigger problem, right?

00:45:55.180 --> 00:45:55.750
Max.

00:45:55.750 --> 00:45:57.410
AUDIENCE: Quick question.

00:45:57.410 --> 00:46:00.660
You said that we're not very
good at going in covered wagons

00:46:00.660 --> 00:46:01.160
east.

00:46:01.160 --> 00:46:04.440
Is there anyone that is?

00:46:04.440 --> 00:46:08.260
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: You know,
developing countries that

00:46:08.260 --> 00:46:12.100
don't have mature
legacy sectors tend

00:46:12.100 --> 00:46:16.120
to be able to innovate
in many, many areas.

00:46:16.120 --> 00:46:19.450
So that is the story
of the stunning growth

00:46:19.450 --> 00:46:23.410
numbers that China has built
over the last 30 years, right?

00:46:23.410 --> 00:46:25.990
Because there wasn't
much there, so they

00:46:25.990 --> 00:46:28.360
didn't have to overcome
these legacy sectors.

00:46:28.360 --> 00:46:31.430
They were working in
innovating in every sector.

00:46:31.430 --> 00:46:36.160
So they build this remarkable
10% a year growth rate.

00:46:36.160 --> 00:46:37.990
They've now built
out a lot of it.

00:46:37.990 --> 00:46:40.830
So their growth rate is going
to finally come down a bit

00:46:40.830 --> 00:46:43.180
and it's starting to do so.

00:46:43.180 --> 00:46:45.430
But that gives you a signal
of the kind of growth rate

00:46:45.430 --> 00:46:49.070
you could have if you were able
to innovate across the board,

00:46:49.070 --> 00:46:51.360
not just in frontier areas.

00:46:51.360 --> 00:46:51.860
Martha.

00:46:51.860 --> 00:46:54.068
AUDIENCE: But is it not just
because they didn't have

00:46:54.068 --> 00:46:57.390
anything there in China,
because they're so top-down,

00:46:57.390 --> 00:46:57.890
they could--

00:46:57.890 --> 00:46:58.180
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Yeah.

00:46:58.180 --> 00:47:00.490
I mean, there's organizational
issues like that too.

00:47:00.490 --> 00:47:07.990
But you can look at Korea,
you're looking at Taiwan,

00:47:07.990 --> 00:47:11.920
and you can look at the IT
economy in India, right?

00:47:11.920 --> 00:47:17.590
Another staggering success story
of stunning rates of advance.

00:47:17.590 --> 00:47:20.290
The government had
kind of fenced off

00:47:20.290 --> 00:47:24.850
most of hard industries into a
fairly socialist kind of system

00:47:24.850 --> 00:47:27.170
and pretty inefficient.

00:47:27.170 --> 00:47:29.770
They haven't fenced
off the IT sector

00:47:29.770 --> 00:47:34.240
and that was not a
heavy governmental hand,

00:47:34.240 --> 00:47:36.490
that was just take off, right?

00:47:36.490 --> 00:47:37.720
And it's a remarkable story.

00:47:37.720 --> 00:47:39.850
So it's not always the
way-- you don't always

00:47:39.850 --> 00:47:44.620
need that governmentally hand,
but it's an important point.

00:47:44.620 --> 00:47:47.990
So the US just doesn't
do this very well.

00:47:47.990 --> 00:47:51.370
The example on the
slide is, we don't

00:47:51.370 --> 00:47:53.590
go back and fix the health
care delivery system.

00:47:53.590 --> 00:47:56.750
We've been fighting over
that for about 15 years.

00:47:56.750 --> 00:47:59.350
We're pretty good at
doing biotech, right?

00:47:59.350 --> 00:48:00.850
That worked.

00:48:00.850 --> 00:48:03.270
But taking on a whole
health care delivery system

00:48:03.270 --> 00:48:06.400
has proved elusive
to say the least.

00:48:06.400 --> 00:48:08.105
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:48:08.105 --> 00:48:10.480
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Yeah,
hospitals and the whole service

00:48:10.480 --> 00:48:11.890
side of health care.

00:48:11.890 --> 00:48:15.630
And there's technology
tied to that across, too.

00:48:15.630 --> 00:48:20.480
So a complex established sector
is not a level playing field,

00:48:20.480 --> 00:48:20.980
right?

00:48:20.980 --> 00:48:23.620
One of the advantages
of technology

00:48:23.620 --> 00:48:26.100
stand up in a frontier
is there's no incumbent,

00:48:26.100 --> 00:48:27.080
you just do it.

00:48:27.080 --> 00:48:27.580
Right?

00:48:27.580 --> 00:48:29.650
That's the India story, right?

00:48:29.650 --> 00:48:32.678
That's the story of the
IT revolution in the US.

00:48:32.678 --> 00:48:34.720
There wasn't anything
really quite like computing

00:48:34.720 --> 00:48:36.400
before computing, it just--

00:48:36.400 --> 00:48:39.820
there was nobody in the way.

00:48:39.820 --> 00:48:45.250
Similarly, biotech didn't
really have anybody in the way,

00:48:45.250 --> 00:48:47.680
whereas these health care
delivery or energy problems are

00:48:47.680 --> 00:48:51.460
much more complicated because
you're up against established

00:48:51.460 --> 00:48:52.300
incumbents.

00:48:52.300 --> 00:48:58.120
And these incumbents have strong
technology models and systems

00:48:58.120 --> 00:49:00.430
often with vast
infrastructure, right?

00:49:00.430 --> 00:49:04.480
Think about gas stations
and gas pipeline systems.

00:49:04.480 --> 00:49:07.270
They have an economic model and
they've driven down the cost

00:49:07.270 --> 00:49:09.910
curve, so it's a
remarkably efficient system

00:49:09.910 --> 00:49:13.600
with remarkably low
energy prices in the US.

00:49:13.600 --> 00:49:16.870
There's a massive political
support system, right?

00:49:16.870 --> 00:49:21.490
These are strong regional
employers and important parts

00:49:21.490 --> 00:49:23.080
of local and regional
economies, they

00:49:23.080 --> 00:49:25.900
are very strong politically.

00:49:25.900 --> 00:49:29.020
And there's a whole
social support system.

00:49:29.020 --> 00:49:33.190
For many decades, chemical
engineering departments

00:49:33.190 --> 00:49:37.510
were essentially at every
unit major university,

00:49:37.510 --> 00:49:40.350
were essentially part of
the fossil fuel system.

00:49:40.350 --> 00:49:43.000
That's obviously
changed, but there

00:49:43.000 --> 00:49:47.590
was a whole set of
academic social support

00:49:47.590 --> 00:49:49.150
systems that are there.

00:49:49.150 --> 00:49:52.780
And, look, the US public
has an expectation

00:49:52.780 --> 00:49:55.040
that we get cheap energy prices.

00:49:55.040 --> 00:49:55.540
Right?

00:49:55.540 --> 00:49:58.850
Try taking that one
on, politically, right?

00:49:58.850 --> 00:50:00.850
That's one of the political
problems with trying

00:50:00.850 --> 00:50:02.960
to impose a carbon tax.

00:50:02.960 --> 00:50:04.570
What a wonderful message--

00:50:04.570 --> 00:50:07.870
hey, all your energy prices
are going to go up, you know?

00:50:07.870 --> 00:50:12.405
It's not a terribly
attractive political message.

00:50:12.405 --> 00:50:14.530
And part of the problem
here is that the new energy

00:50:14.530 --> 00:50:18.580
technologies have got to be
price competitive the moment

00:50:18.580 --> 00:50:21.420
they arrive in the marketplace.

00:50:21.420 --> 00:50:24.070
So we'll get to that
problem in a minute.

00:50:24.070 --> 00:50:27.200
A carbon charge was going
to be a way to adjust this.

00:50:27.200 --> 00:50:30.670
In other words, it would bring
the fossil fuel prices up,

00:50:30.670 --> 00:50:32.470
and therefore, the
new technologies

00:50:32.470 --> 00:50:35.860
didn't have to drive down nearly
as much down the cost curve.

00:50:35.860 --> 00:50:38.230
It would be easy
to introduce them.

00:50:38.230 --> 00:50:40.661
They, in effect, have a
significant incentive.

00:50:43.370 --> 00:50:45.500
We're not going to
do that, at least

00:50:45.500 --> 00:50:47.790
for a significant
period of time.

00:50:47.790 --> 00:50:50.600
So what do we do?

00:50:50.600 --> 00:50:52.400
Some things we've
talked about already,

00:50:52.400 --> 00:50:54.860
we've got to have a
large program that's

00:50:54.860 --> 00:50:57.667
sizable in scope.

00:50:57.667 --> 00:50:59.750
In the US, it's going to
have to be private-sector

00:50:59.750 --> 00:51:05.000
led because that's where all the
technology and infrastructure

00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:06.650
is.

00:51:06.650 --> 00:51:11.372
Government doesn't control
it except in certain ways.

00:51:11.372 --> 00:51:13.580
That means a public-private
partnership kind of model

00:51:13.580 --> 00:51:15.200
is going to be needed.

00:51:15.200 --> 00:51:17.300
You've got this problem
of technology neutrality

00:51:17.300 --> 00:51:21.080
and avoiding technology lock-in.

00:51:21.080 --> 00:51:22.790
And, again, we're
going to have to think

00:51:22.790 --> 00:51:26.910
about organizing this one we're
getting into now around launch

00:51:26.910 --> 00:51:27.410
pathways.

00:51:27.410 --> 00:51:31.880
So we came up with a kind of
a four-step way of looking

00:51:31.880 --> 00:51:34.350
at launching technologies.

00:51:34.350 --> 00:51:38.065
So there's lots of
literature on R&D

00:51:38.065 --> 00:51:40.190
and you've read now a fair
amount of it by the time

00:51:40.190 --> 00:51:43.010
we reach class 10 here.

00:51:43.010 --> 00:51:46.640
But there's very little
literature on market launch.

00:51:46.640 --> 00:51:51.770
It just is not a topic
that has been taken up

00:51:51.770 --> 00:51:55.100
by the science and
technology policy literature.

00:51:55.100 --> 00:52:01.040
So the essentially idea was,
think about launch pathways.

00:52:01.040 --> 00:52:03.810
Different technologies going
to launch in different ways.

00:52:03.810 --> 00:52:06.320
Launching batteries into
an automotive sector

00:52:06.320 --> 00:52:12.770
is a really different project
than launching biofuels

00:52:12.770 --> 00:52:13.970
into the transport sector.

00:52:16.790 --> 00:52:18.650
But figure out the
launch pathways

00:52:18.650 --> 00:52:20.240
and figure out for
some common launch

00:52:20.240 --> 00:52:22.630
pathways that certain
kinds of technologies have,

00:52:22.630 --> 00:52:24.590
and we'll get to
that in a second.

00:52:24.590 --> 00:52:29.570
Then, step two is tie those
launch pathways to whatever

00:52:29.570 --> 00:52:35.190
means of policy support you can
put to those launch pathways,

00:52:35.190 --> 00:52:37.160
right?

00:52:37.160 --> 00:52:39.260
Do a gap analysis in
the innovation system,

00:52:39.260 --> 00:52:42.320
both front end and
back end, and then

00:52:42.320 --> 00:52:44.810
work on filling in the gaps
in that innovation system.

00:52:44.810 --> 00:52:46.790
So a four-step process.

00:52:46.790 --> 00:52:49.940
We'll take these
apart for a minute.

00:52:49.940 --> 00:52:52.430
The US has never tried to do
anything this tough, right?

00:52:52.430 --> 00:52:55.160
I think there have been
technology challenges

00:52:55.160 --> 00:52:57.770
themselves that are
harder than this, right?

00:52:57.770 --> 00:53:00.332
Because we can kind
of see the strands

00:53:00.332 --> 00:53:02.540
that we're going to get over
the next 25 or 30 years.

00:53:02.540 --> 00:53:03.320
They're kind of out there.

00:53:03.320 --> 00:53:05.090
We kind of know what
solar is going to be like,

00:53:05.090 --> 00:53:07.075
we kind of know what
wind is going to be like,

00:53:07.075 --> 00:53:08.450
we can see what's
going to happen

00:53:08.450 --> 00:53:10.790
in storage to some extent.

00:53:10.790 --> 00:53:13.620
We kind of know what the
paths are going to be.

00:53:13.620 --> 00:53:15.993
And these are not--

00:53:15.993 --> 00:53:18.410
this is not like the Manhattan
Project, that was a tougher

00:53:18.410 --> 00:53:20.310
technology project.

00:53:20.310 --> 00:53:23.960
But this is such a tough
implementation task,

00:53:23.960 --> 00:53:28.200
we have never ever tried to do
anything this complex before.

00:53:28.200 --> 00:53:32.400
So it's a challenge
worthy of your careers.

00:53:32.400 --> 00:53:34.950
It is the big one.

00:53:34.950 --> 00:53:35.483
Martin?

00:53:35.483 --> 00:53:36.900
AUDIENCE: So your
focus is policy,

00:53:36.900 --> 00:53:40.300
Weis's is government because
you both wrote a book together,

00:53:40.300 --> 00:53:40.928
right?

