00:55:51.160 --> 00:55:53.100
So let's go back
to step one we'll

00:55:53.100 --> 00:55:56.500
do a little more detail here so
you get what I'm talking about.

00:55:56.500 --> 00:55:59.190
Let's categorize the
launch categories, right?

00:55:59.190 --> 00:56:02.730
So we know we've got to
do a bunch of wedges--

00:56:02.730 --> 00:56:04.440
different technologies
often embedded

00:56:04.440 --> 00:56:07.830
in each different wedge.

00:56:07.830 --> 00:56:09.960
How do we look at
launch pathways

00:56:09.960 --> 00:56:12.060
as a way of looking at
the different launch

00:56:12.060 --> 00:56:14.980
pathways in energy, and
seeing if some are similar,

00:56:14.980 --> 00:56:17.090
then you could aggregate
the policy support

00:56:17.090 --> 00:56:18.250
mechanisms around those.

00:56:18.250 --> 00:56:23.040
So some technologies
are experimental,

00:56:23.040 --> 00:56:25.710
and are just going to
require long term research.

00:56:25.710 --> 00:56:28.090
So Max, that's
your paper, right?

00:56:28.090 --> 00:56:32.580
Fusion is still long
term, incredible potential

00:56:32.580 --> 00:56:34.560
if we could get there.

00:56:34.560 --> 00:56:36.620
We're not really
ready for much more

00:56:36.620 --> 00:56:40.060
beyond R&D and some
demonstration commitments

00:56:40.060 --> 00:56:42.210
at this stage.

00:56:42.210 --> 00:56:45.990
So that's a federal R&D role--

00:56:45.990 --> 00:56:49.820
hydrogen fuel cells, a
similar kind of problem.

00:56:49.820 --> 00:56:52.070
So that's experimental
technologies--

00:56:52.070 --> 00:56:53.330
that's one category.

00:56:53.330 --> 00:56:55.900
Just do R&D for those folks.

00:56:55.900 --> 00:56:59.420
The second category would
be potentially disruptive

00:56:59.420 --> 00:57:01.750
innovations that could be
launched in-- you guessed it,

00:57:01.750 --> 00:57:02.660
Martin--

00:57:02.660 --> 00:57:05.030
niche markets, right?

00:57:05.030 --> 00:57:09.740
So that's typically
how induced innovation

00:57:09.740 --> 00:57:11.788
works in the private sector.

00:57:11.788 --> 00:57:14.330
A private sector company will
identify market opportunities--

00:57:14.330 --> 00:57:16.490
typically a niche market--

00:57:16.490 --> 00:57:19.505
take that market, move into
it, and start to scale up

00:57:19.505 --> 00:57:21.110
a new technology advance.

00:57:21.110 --> 00:57:25.280
That's the LED story--
remarkable success story.

00:57:25.280 --> 00:57:27.350
They found niche
markets that couldn't

00:57:27.350 --> 00:57:31.730
be dealt with by either
of their incandescent

00:57:31.730 --> 00:57:34.940
or fluorescent
technology competitors.

00:57:34.940 --> 00:57:38.726
They found niche markets
where LEDs were--

00:57:38.726 --> 00:57:41.690
a so much better answer
than the competitors,

00:57:41.690 --> 00:57:44.150
and then they scaled
into those niche markets,

00:57:44.150 --> 00:57:47.120
and they used that
opportunity to drive the price

00:57:47.120 --> 00:57:49.580
down so that, when
the time came,

00:57:49.580 --> 00:57:52.760
they could actually compete
over that extended time

00:57:52.760 --> 00:57:54.560
period of driving the
cost down to compete

00:57:54.560 --> 00:57:55.518
with the other sectors.

00:57:55.518 --> 00:57:59.570
So that's a classic example of
launching into a niche market.

00:57:59.570 --> 00:58:02.780
Solar PV has had some of
that opportunity as well--

00:58:02.780 --> 00:58:07.340
that's been launched into
a bunch of niche markets.

00:58:07.340 --> 00:58:09.330
But then, there's a more
complicated category,

00:58:09.330 --> 00:58:11.840
and these are--

00:58:11.840 --> 00:58:13.820
we'll call them
secondary innovations,

00:58:13.820 --> 00:58:15.770
or component
innovations, and this

00:58:15.770 --> 00:58:18.350
is a lot of what energy is.

00:58:18.350 --> 00:58:20.450
Secondary innovations
are components

00:58:20.450 --> 00:58:26.270
in larger systems that face
immediate price competition

00:58:26.270 --> 00:58:33.200
based on price, but they can
launch in an uncontested way

00:58:33.200 --> 00:58:38.080
if the owner of that larger
system wants them, right?

00:58:38.080 --> 00:58:44.770
If that technology is acceptable
to that system owner, operator,

00:58:44.770 --> 00:58:45.910
then they can be accepted.

00:58:45.910 --> 00:58:47.702
So all they have to do
is drive price down,

00:58:47.702 --> 00:58:49.360
and then they can
come in, right?

00:58:49.360 --> 00:58:52.940
So batteries for
plug-in hybrids--

00:58:52.940 --> 00:58:56.320
that's a great
example here, right?

00:58:56.320 --> 00:59:00.880
The auto sector-- they've been
burned so many times by fossil

00:59:00.880 --> 00:59:03.490
fuel prices that's
complete wrecked them--

00:59:03.490 --> 00:59:06.490
we're on time number three now--

00:59:06.490 --> 00:59:10.930
that they're happy to have a
much larger share of hybrids,

00:59:10.930 --> 00:59:15.490
or indeed electrics, in
their auto portfolio.

00:59:15.490 --> 00:59:18.040
So this would not be a
contested launch-- they're

00:59:18.040 --> 00:59:20.030
willing to take this stuff.

00:59:20.030 --> 00:59:21.610
But you've got to
get the price down,

00:59:21.610 --> 00:59:24.068
which we still haven't been
able to achieve yet from really

00:59:24.068 --> 00:59:25.210
widespread introduction.

00:59:25.210 --> 00:59:29.470
But that would be an example
of a secondary innovation

00:59:29.470 --> 00:59:32.900
with an uncontested launch.

00:59:32.900 --> 00:59:38.180
The hard stuff is
secondary innovations

00:59:38.180 --> 00:59:39.920
with a contested launch.

00:59:39.920 --> 00:59:43.410
That's carbon capture
and sequestration.

00:59:43.410 --> 00:59:46.880
So the message to a utility
company in that situation is--

00:59:49.590 --> 00:59:54.310
hi, we want you to do carbon
capture and sequestration.

00:59:54.310 --> 00:59:58.960
This is going to reduce the
efficiency of your plant by 40%

00:59:58.960 --> 01:00:02.070
and add 50% to your costs, or
numbers somewhat like those.

01:00:02.070 --> 01:00:03.470
Is that ballpark
numbers, Martha?

01:00:03.470 --> 01:00:04.970
Is that in range?

01:00:04.970 --> 01:00:06.520
MARTHA: And there's no upside--

01:00:06.520 --> 01:00:07.415
I mean there's no financial--

01:00:07.415 --> 01:00:09.498
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Yeah,
what's the benefit here?

01:00:09.498 --> 01:00:11.170
And finance it too--

01:00:11.170 --> 01:00:12.910
you finance it, right?

01:00:12.910 --> 01:00:15.520
And nail your utility
customers, right?

01:00:15.520 --> 01:00:16.280
Good luck.

01:00:16.280 --> 01:00:16.780
Right?

01:00:16.780 --> 01:00:18.760
That's what you call
a contested launch.

01:00:18.760 --> 01:00:20.920
The only way these people
are going to do this

01:00:20.920 --> 01:00:24.077
is if you tell them--

01:00:24.077 --> 01:00:25.660
they're going to
violate criminal laws

01:00:25.660 --> 01:00:26.480
unless they do it.

01:00:26.480 --> 01:00:27.820
I mean, that's about
all you can do here.

01:00:27.820 --> 01:00:29.530
You have to regulate
these, right?

01:00:29.530 --> 01:00:32.680
There's no other move.

01:00:32.680 --> 01:00:34.790
I mean, there are some
other categories here, too,

01:00:34.790 --> 01:00:38.440
that we need conservation and
end-use efficiency always needs

01:00:38.440 --> 01:00:41.320
work, and advances
in manufacturing--

01:00:41.320 --> 01:00:42.610
technologies for scale up.

01:00:42.610 --> 01:00:44.290
Those are important
as well, but these

01:00:44.290 --> 01:00:49.040
are the four major territories,
the four major launch pathways,

01:00:49.040 --> 01:00:49.540
we have.

01:00:49.540 --> 01:00:53.680
And then we've got a whole set
of policy packages, all right?

01:00:53.680 --> 01:00:56.200
So for front end support, right?

01:00:56.200 --> 01:00:59.110
We do R&D, and--

01:00:59.110 --> 01:01:01.480
it would be great to
grow some of that R&D.

01:01:01.480 --> 01:01:03.400
That will help us with
experimental, that'll

01:01:03.400 --> 01:01:05.480
help us in all four
categories, because all

01:01:05.480 --> 01:01:08.950
these technologies need work.

01:01:08.950 --> 01:01:13.540
Back end incentives, to
encourage the technology

01:01:13.540 --> 01:01:16.150
deployment, right?

01:01:16.150 --> 01:01:19.180
That's really needed for
secondary or component

01:01:19.180 --> 01:01:24.130
technologies, particularly
when they've gotten--

01:01:24.130 --> 01:01:26.460
the need for both
contested and uncontested.

01:01:26.460 --> 01:01:30.730
But you could really use
these incentives to encourage,

01:01:30.730 --> 01:01:33.190
and we've done it, lower
prices of automobiles

01:01:33.190 --> 01:01:35.200
that happen to be hybrids
or electrics, right?

01:01:35.200 --> 01:01:36.130
So we've done those.

01:01:36.130 --> 01:01:37.930
You can see what I'm
talking about here--

01:01:37.930 --> 01:01:40.780
tax credits, loan
guarantees, price guarantees,

01:01:40.780 --> 01:01:43.990
government procurement programs,
new product buy-down programs--

01:01:43.990 --> 01:01:46.120
we've tried a whole
series of these.

01:01:46.120 --> 01:01:48.640
And Congress just renewed
a lot of the tax incentives

01:01:48.640 --> 01:01:51.010
that have been so
important to wind and solar

01:01:51.010 --> 01:01:52.780
for a multi-year
period last year,

01:01:52.780 --> 01:01:55.720
so those are going to
remain in place for a while.

01:01:55.720 --> 01:02:00.370
But front end, R&D support.

01:02:00.370 --> 01:02:03.130
Back-end incentives,
carrots-- typically

01:02:03.130 --> 01:02:05.740
for uncontested launch.

01:02:05.740 --> 01:02:09.957
Niche-- remember, the industry,
if it can find a market niche,

01:02:09.957 --> 01:02:11.290
you don't have to do this stuff.

01:02:11.290 --> 01:02:13.857
They're going to need help on
the front end R&D probably,

01:02:13.857 --> 01:02:15.940
but if you can launch into
a market niche-- that's

01:02:15.940 --> 01:02:18.398
why it's so attractive to try
and find a market niche where

01:02:18.398 --> 01:02:20.230
we can launch these
technologies, right?

01:02:20.230 --> 01:02:22.750
Because that's a way of
starting to scale up,

01:02:22.750 --> 01:02:26.740
and then buying yourself time
to drive down the price curve.

01:02:26.740 --> 01:02:30.580
The hard one is sticks, right?

01:02:30.580 --> 01:02:33.310
So for secondary technologies
where you're going to have

01:02:33.310 --> 01:02:36.280
a contested launch-- the
industry sector doesn't want

01:02:36.280 --> 01:02:38.440
it--

01:02:38.440 --> 01:02:40.630
you're going to have to
use regulatory requirements

01:02:40.630 --> 01:02:44.300
and mandates to require
this to occur, right?

01:02:44.300 --> 01:02:48.290
And-- a carbon tax
is a form of this.

01:02:48.290 --> 01:02:52.730
It's organized around-- creating
a new kind of financial reality

01:02:52.730 --> 01:02:54.050
for these kinds of firms.

01:02:54.050 --> 01:02:59.570
So pick your energy
technology, see

01:02:59.570 --> 01:03:01.550
if you can group it
into a launch category,

01:03:01.550 --> 01:03:05.390
and then step two-- tie
your incentive package

01:03:05.390 --> 01:03:08.210
to those launch pathways.

01:03:08.210 --> 01:03:10.750
Follow me so far?

01:03:10.750 --> 01:03:13.350
OK.

01:03:13.350 --> 01:03:16.780
Step three-- you're
familiar with this by now--

01:03:16.780 --> 01:03:18.530
look at the gaps in
the innovation system,

01:03:18.530 --> 01:03:20.420
and you've got to look at
the gaps on the front end,

01:03:20.420 --> 01:03:22.590
and you got to look at
the gaps in the back end

01:03:22.590 --> 01:03:24.200
of the innovation system.

01:03:24.200 --> 01:03:26.390
And then step four--

01:03:26.390 --> 01:03:26.990
duh.

01:03:26.990 --> 01:03:31.130
Fill the gaps, right?

01:03:31.130 --> 01:03:33.070
In that innovation pipeline.

01:03:33.070 --> 01:03:35.730
And that moves from every stage,
from research and development,

01:03:35.730 --> 01:03:37.730
all the way through
prototype and demonstration,

01:03:37.730 --> 01:03:40.700
and testing, and deployment,
into a commercial market--

01:03:40.700 --> 01:03:43.100
you've got to look at all
of those stages, right?

01:03:43.100 --> 01:03:47.390
And the production phase
too, as we've talked about.

01:03:47.390 --> 01:03:49.840
We've talked about identifying
the gaps in the innovation

01:03:49.840 --> 01:03:50.340
system--

01:03:50.340 --> 01:03:51.980
I'm going to skip this--

01:03:51.980 --> 01:03:55.250
some mechanisms that we'll talk
about in this class for filling

01:03:55.250 --> 01:03:56.780
some of those gaps.

01:03:56.780 --> 01:03:59.930
ARPA-E, arguably-- and we'll
talk about this in a bit--

01:03:59.930 --> 01:04:02.660
filled a gap in the
US energy R&D system

01:04:02.660 --> 01:04:07.100
for breakthrough
technology advances.

01:04:07.100 --> 01:04:10.070
Maybe we need a better
government mechanism

01:04:10.070 --> 01:04:13.920
for large scale
testing and deployment.

01:04:13.920 --> 01:04:17.810
There's a sore need in carbon
capture and sequestration,

01:04:17.810 --> 01:04:21.080
and we lack a
government corporation

01:04:21.080 --> 01:04:23.528
that can conduct this kind
of demonstration level.

01:04:23.528 --> 01:04:25.070
That's part of the
reason why we just

01:04:25.070 --> 01:04:27.403
haven't been able to get there
in terms of demonstration

01:04:27.403 --> 01:04:29.240
of that technology.

01:04:29.240 --> 01:04:33.020
Those are some gap standards--
test beds are part of the gaps.

01:04:33.020 --> 01:04:37.300
In energy, there is this big
problem of new functionality.

01:04:37.300 --> 01:04:42.550
That's a technology problem you
need to understand in energy.

01:04:42.550 --> 01:04:48.660
IT created new functionality
from the outset.

01:04:48.660 --> 01:04:50.720
So you've heard me
tell this story before.

01:04:50.720 --> 01:04:54.500
I was happy to spend a
ridiculous amount of money

01:04:54.500 --> 01:05:00.530
on my Apple 2E because it
did all kinds of stuff for me

01:05:00.530 --> 01:05:03.470
that I couldn't
do before, right?

01:05:03.470 --> 01:05:05.510
That would be new functionality.

01:05:05.510 --> 01:05:09.930
Spreadsheets, all kinds
of stuff like that, right?

01:05:09.930 --> 01:05:13.200
Energy technologies--
first generation,

01:05:13.200 --> 01:05:17.662
by and large, don't give
you new functionality.

01:05:17.662 --> 01:05:19.245
The nice thing about
new functionality

01:05:19.245 --> 01:05:22.620
is that people are willing
to pay a premium if they

01:05:22.620 --> 01:05:24.810
can do something entirely new.

01:05:24.810 --> 01:05:28.470
But I don't know
whether my laptop

01:05:28.470 --> 01:05:34.590
is plugged into coal or nuclear
power, or hydro, or the sun--

01:05:34.590 --> 01:05:35.910
I have no idea, right?

01:05:35.910 --> 01:05:38.700
There's no product
differentiation for me

01:05:38.700 --> 01:05:40.510
in the way in which
I get electricity.

01:05:40.510 --> 01:05:42.235
Now some utilities--

01:05:42.235 --> 01:05:43.860
Connecticut is an
interesting example--

01:05:43.860 --> 01:05:46.740
are attempting to
create that background

01:05:46.740 --> 01:05:49.440
knowledge for consumers, so they
can actually pick technologies

01:05:49.440 --> 01:05:51.430
they're interested
in, but that's

01:05:51.430 --> 01:05:53.520
not a widespread model yet.

01:05:53.520 --> 01:05:56.790
So there's not much new
functionality in electricity--

01:05:56.790 --> 01:06:00.090
they're all still electrons.

01:06:00.090 --> 01:06:03.030
It's tough to do
product differentiation.

01:06:05.910 --> 01:06:08.310
Cars, right?

01:06:08.310 --> 01:06:15.350
There is a difference
between a Tesla and--

01:06:15.350 --> 01:06:18.660
the thing I drive, right?

01:06:18.660 --> 01:06:24.360
Because if you happen to be into
rapid torque and acceleration,

01:06:24.360 --> 01:06:27.300
Tesla does provide you
similar functionality--

01:06:27.300 --> 01:06:29.090
but that's about it.

01:06:29.090 --> 01:06:31.100
In most driving
circumstances, it's just not

01:06:31.100 --> 01:06:32.850
all that different,
and a hybrid certainly

01:06:32.850 --> 01:06:35.430
is not all that different.

01:06:35.430 --> 01:06:38.670
Tesla brilliantly
figured out, as did

01:06:38.670 --> 01:06:46.500
Prius, brand differentiation
in their market launch.

01:06:46.500 --> 01:06:50.010
They figured out how to
create a really cool vehicle,

01:06:50.010 --> 01:06:52.980
and you could sell it on
your image of yourself

01:06:52.980 --> 01:06:54.798
as being cool for
buying a Tesla, right?

01:06:54.798 --> 01:06:56.215
It worked very
well in California,

01:06:56.215 --> 01:06:57.880
and still does does, right?

01:06:57.880 --> 01:07:00.307
And Prius did something
similar, right?

01:07:00.307 --> 01:07:01.890
You're not just
driving a car-- you're

01:07:01.890 --> 01:07:05.640
bragging about your
environmental outlook

01:07:05.640 --> 01:07:06.690
on the world, right?

01:07:06.690 --> 01:07:09.480
So this is a way of
getting around the fact

01:07:09.480 --> 01:07:11.910
that there isn't that much
product differentiation,

01:07:11.910 --> 01:07:13.850
there's not that
much functionality

01:07:13.850 --> 01:07:15.220
in the energy sector.

01:07:15.220 --> 01:07:18.720
I think there will be.

01:07:18.720 --> 01:07:21.690
I'd like to--

01:07:21.690 --> 01:07:24.330
LEDs are quite neat,
and you can have

01:07:24.330 --> 01:07:27.140
a light wall, or a light floor.

01:07:27.140 --> 01:07:29.250
And I'd pay for that--

01:07:29.250 --> 01:07:32.620
that would be cool, as opposed
to a light bulb hanging

01:07:32.620 --> 01:07:34.790
overhead.

01:07:34.790 --> 01:07:37.350
That's new functionality,
so I'd pay for that.

01:07:37.350 --> 01:07:40.770
But that's not first generation
of energy technologies--

01:07:40.770 --> 01:07:42.930
that's not happening yet.

01:07:42.930 --> 01:07:49.270
It's harder to create product
differentiation and new

01:07:49.270 --> 01:07:51.370
functionality in the
first generation of energy

01:07:51.370 --> 01:07:55.420
technologies, which
underscores how complicated

01:07:55.420 --> 01:07:56.440
the market launch is.

01:07:58.678 --> 01:08:00.220
AUDIENCE: There are
some technologies

01:08:00.220 --> 01:08:01.952
that can offer new
functionality, if not

01:08:01.952 --> 01:08:03.952
for the consumer, then
for the people are paying

01:08:03.952 --> 01:08:06.260
for it-- like the utility.

01:08:06.260 --> 01:08:07.580
One example would be--

01:08:07.580 --> 01:08:09.033
fusion produces
lots of neutrons,

01:08:09.033 --> 01:08:11.200
and you could use that to
get rid of nuclear waste--

01:08:11.200 --> 01:08:14.198
could be nice, and there's
virtually nothing else

01:08:14.198 --> 01:08:14.990
that could do that.

01:08:14.990 --> 01:08:16.073
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Right.

01:08:16.073 --> 01:08:19.404
So yes, that may be the silver
bullet-- we're just still

01:08:19.404 --> 01:08:20.459
a while away from it.

01:08:20.459 --> 01:08:23.001
AUDIENCE: Nuclear waste is like,
a trillion dollar market, so

01:08:23.001 --> 01:08:23.501
[INAUDIBLE].

01:08:23.501 --> 01:08:24.584
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Right.

01:08:24.584 --> 01:08:26.640
And the problem for
the utility companies

01:08:26.640 --> 01:08:29.040
is, to adopt new technologies
they-- generally speaking--

01:08:29.040 --> 01:08:30.510
have to pay more, right?

01:08:30.510 --> 01:08:33.050
Although we're working on
driving those costs down.

01:08:33.050 --> 01:08:33.240
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:08:33.240 --> 01:08:34.350
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: We
made a lot of progress.

01:08:34.350 --> 01:08:37.410
AUDIENCE: What I'd look into
[INAUDIBLE] like a process,

01:08:37.410 --> 01:08:42.240
it's a whole supply chain
for energy, so lines,

01:08:42.240 --> 01:08:45.870
where you produce it, when it
gets over, and what dissipates.

01:08:45.870 --> 01:08:48.210
So figuring out how
the supply chain

01:08:48.210 --> 01:08:51.812
is flawed to create products
that fix the supply chain,

01:08:51.812 --> 01:08:54.270
so it's a lot better, and they
don't have those [INAUDIBLE]

01:08:54.270 --> 01:08:55.140
by the way.

01:08:55.140 --> 01:08:57.000
That's the product, right?

01:08:57.000 --> 01:08:59.859
This system is broken, I fix
the system with this product,

01:08:59.859 --> 01:09:02.130
and so because energy
is going to come out

01:09:02.130 --> 01:09:04.140
either way the same way, right?

01:09:04.140 --> 01:09:05.460
That's how I think about it.

01:09:05.460 --> 01:09:05.910
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Right, and you

01:09:05.910 --> 01:09:08.520
can think about smart grid
options that do create

01:09:08.520 --> 01:09:10.229
new functionalities as well

01:09:10.229 --> 01:09:11.646
AUDIENCE: Or mobile
energy sources

01:09:11.646 --> 01:09:13.812
that can be near cities,
because then you don't have

01:09:13.812 --> 01:09:15.000
to transport them long ways.

01:09:15.000 --> 01:09:17.910
And-- especially for
disrupting big companies,

01:09:17.910 --> 01:09:20.357
they spend so much money
on putting the lines,

01:09:20.357 --> 01:09:21.899
and they have to
pay for regulations,

01:09:21.899 --> 01:09:23.380
and it slows them down.

01:09:23.380 --> 01:09:26.967
So a new mover can do something
like that, and disrupt them.

01:09:26.967 --> 01:09:28.050
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Right.

01:09:28.050 --> 01:09:30.187
Finding those market
niches is a task

01:09:30.187 --> 01:09:31.770
that is now upon us,
because we're not

01:09:31.770 --> 01:09:34.859
going to do a carbon tax.

01:09:34.859 --> 01:09:37.770
So let me just
recap for a minute.

01:09:37.770 --> 01:09:40.620
You have to apply all
the innovation models--

01:09:40.620 --> 01:09:43.500
pipeline, induced,
extended, manufacturing led,

01:09:43.500 --> 01:09:44.640
innovation, organization.

01:09:44.640 --> 01:09:46.979
You've got to think about
this, and [INAUDIBLE]

01:09:46.979 --> 01:09:49.470
by looking at all the
dynamics of innovation

01:09:49.470 --> 01:09:51.720
and how to organize them.

01:09:51.720 --> 01:09:54.210
And we need the four step
process here-- figure out

01:09:54.210 --> 01:09:58.920
the launch categories, group
them with similar technologies,

01:09:58.920 --> 01:10:03.320
apply the right incentive
package to that category.

01:10:03.320 --> 01:10:05.070
Look at the gaps in
the innovation system,

01:10:05.070 --> 01:10:06.720
and work on filling those gaps.

01:10:06.720 --> 01:10:12.690
So that's the four-step
process we've got so far.

