01:11:22.800 --> 01:11:27.930
MATT: So are there true examples
of really innovating, where you

01:11:27.930 --> 01:11:29.520
already have a legacy sector.

01:11:32.843 --> 01:11:34.260
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
You know, when

01:11:34.260 --> 01:11:38.970
we read that reading on DARPA
a couple of classes ago,

01:11:38.970 --> 01:11:43.590
as we talked about at the
time, the defense sector--

01:11:43.590 --> 01:11:45.420
it's a legacy sector, right?

01:11:45.420 --> 01:11:48.330
It's very locked into
its technologies,

01:11:48.330 --> 01:11:52.440
into its social organization,
into its economic and budgeting

01:11:52.440 --> 01:11:53.640
models.

01:11:53.640 --> 01:11:55.300
It's very hard to
innovate there--

01:11:55.300 --> 01:12:00.030
you're up against a lot of
established systems there.

01:12:00.030 --> 01:12:07.260
Yet DOD has been able to
bring on a whole set of very

01:12:07.260 --> 01:12:09.600
interesting advanced
technologies over the last 25

01:12:09.600 --> 01:12:10.890
or 30 years.

01:12:10.890 --> 01:12:15.840
So it does tell you that this
is not Mission Impossible,

01:12:15.840 --> 01:12:18.690
and there are
organizational lessons--

01:12:18.690 --> 01:12:21.450
as you've read in the textbook--

01:12:21.450 --> 01:12:26.790
that we can pull out of DOD.

01:12:26.790 --> 01:12:29.652
Part of it has to do
with some of the rules

01:12:29.652 --> 01:12:31.110
that we've talked
about previously.

01:12:31.110 --> 01:12:32.690
Part of it has to
do with finding

01:12:32.690 --> 01:12:36.580
a community of change agents,
and that's very, very critical.

01:12:36.580 --> 01:12:39.810
So you need to develop
the new technologies.

01:12:42.430 --> 01:12:45.070
You use an island
bridge model to attempt

01:12:45.070 --> 01:12:47.860
to get the decision
maker community

01:12:47.860 --> 01:12:52.190
to force your approach
on the overall system.

01:12:52.190 --> 01:12:53.815
And then to do that
is going to require

01:12:53.815 --> 01:12:55.930
a community of change agents.

01:12:55.930 --> 01:12:58.378
And there are communities
of change agents

01:12:58.378 --> 01:12:59.920
that we're starting
to see in energy.

01:12:59.920 --> 01:13:04.410
I do think that we are entering
into a very significant energy

01:13:04.410 --> 01:13:06.250
innovation wave,
and we can already

01:13:06.250 --> 01:13:08.960
start to see some
of the outlines.

01:13:08.960 --> 01:13:11.450
We've seen a fracking
revolution in the United States

01:13:11.450 --> 01:13:17.610
that has completely changed
the landscape of US energy

01:13:17.610 --> 01:13:22.430
dependency, and
it's very dramatic.

01:13:22.430 --> 01:13:25.200
I mean, the entire energy supply
system of the United States

01:13:25.200 --> 01:13:27.330
has been turned upside down--

01:13:27.330 --> 01:13:30.650
something which nobody ever
thought was conceivable, right?

01:13:30.650 --> 01:13:32.570
And that is a set of
technology advances

01:13:32.570 --> 01:13:35.300
that were originally pushed
by several of the energy

01:13:35.300 --> 01:13:38.660
laboratories, developed
that core technologies

01:13:38.660 --> 01:13:43.420
behind fracking,
and proceeded to--

01:13:43.420 --> 01:13:46.190
it was implemented over about
a 15-year period as something

01:13:46.190 --> 01:13:49.910
by a wildcat maverick community
in the natural gas sector that

01:13:49.910 --> 01:13:53.930
took these technologies up and
worked on implementing them,

01:13:53.930 --> 01:13:55.910
and it really changed things.

01:13:55.910 --> 01:13:58.220
And the United States leads
that technology revolution,

01:13:58.220 --> 01:14:00.800
so we have 100,000-- now
there's a lot of debate

01:14:00.800 --> 01:14:03.920
about a lot of these operations,
the environmental consequences

01:14:03.920 --> 01:14:05.030
of them.

01:14:05.030 --> 01:14:10.280
We have about 100,000, roughly,
net fracking operations

01:14:10.280 --> 01:14:12.200
ongoing now in
the United States.

01:14:12.200 --> 01:14:16.290
The country closest to us is
China-- it has about 6,000,

01:14:16.290 --> 01:14:17.300
all right?

01:14:17.300 --> 01:14:21.530
So we have a big lead on that
energy technology revolution.

01:14:21.530 --> 01:14:25.190
We have-- we can see--

01:14:25.190 --> 01:14:27.200
solar and wind
now, which are now

01:14:27.200 --> 01:14:30.830
scaling up to trillion-dollar
worldwide energy sectors.

01:14:30.830 --> 01:14:33.440
They're going to be
very, very big, right?

01:14:33.440 --> 01:14:36.350
So this revolution is
now starting, right?

01:14:36.350 --> 01:14:38.117
The real question for
the US-- and we'll

01:14:38.117 --> 01:14:39.950
talk about this more
later-- is whether it's

01:14:39.950 --> 01:14:41.336
going to play, right?

01:14:41.336 --> 01:14:42.878
Whether it's going
to ride this wave.

01:14:46.223 --> 01:14:48.640
MATT: Yeah, it definitely seems
like a theme of the class.

01:14:48.640 --> 01:14:52.190
DARPA worked-- let's
try ARPA-E for energy,

01:14:52.190 --> 01:14:54.518
or a DARPA-like
